        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2078373871" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6394173043375760590">Even the most well-intentioned wish will go sour if it goes against death.<br/>Using an atmosphere that makes the story itself seem cursed, <i>The Monkey&apos;s Paw</i> conjures up some horrible imagery in the reader&apos;s head without even having to describe it in detail. The mangled monstrosity that knocks at their door <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[when they wish for their dead son to come home <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, is never actually seen. Better for the characters&apos; sanity, but not for the reader&apos;s curiosity, right?<br/><br/>Obviously, it&apos;s n</span>
  <span id="freeText6394173043375760590" style="display:none">Even the most well-intentioned wish will go sour if it goes against death.<br />Using an atmosphere that makes the story itself seem cursed, <i>The Monkey's Paw</i> conjures up some horrible imagery in the reader's head without even having to describe it in detail. The mangled monstrosity that knocks at their door <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[when they wish for their dead son to come home <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, is never actually seen. Better for the characters' sanity, but not for the reader's curiosity, right?<br /><br />Obviously, it's not the first story where characters wish the dead back to life, but it is a strange spiritual predecessor and inspiration to many that came after it. Definitely well-worth a few minutes taken to read it, as it's only 30 pages.</span>
